Local singer Stefanie Sun has delighted fans with a surprise new single that she dropped early on Friday (Jan 29).

Titled What Remains, the song about introspection is composed, produced and written by Sun. The last time she did this was 19 years ago with the song, Someone.

The new track – available on digital platforms – came about after Sun found herself with time on her hands as she wasn’t able to fly overseas for work because of the pandemic. This gave her time to reflect on her memories and also reconnect with people whom she hadn’t seen in a while.

In a press release statement, Sun said that the most significant line in the song for her is the one that roughly translates to, “I haven’t said how much I’ve missed you for fear that I'll miss you once I say it”.

The 42-year-old also said that What Remains is not meant to be sad. “It’s more about self-discovery, tidying up one’s emotions, and then moving on and forward.”

Sun took to Instagram to announce the song and also took the opportunity to wish her fans a happy Chinese New Year.

From all of us at CNA, here's wishing you a happy CNY right back, Stef! 🍊🍊🧧🧧

IKEA will open on Friday (Jun 19) with strict safe distancing measures, although its food and beverage offerings and kids’ facilities will remain closed for now.

Its two outlets at Tampines and Alexandra will reduce opening hours, limit the number of people inside and close their car parks if queues get too long.

More workers will be deployed for crowd control inside and outside the building, including safe distancing ambassadors who will usher customers along.

Staff will increase the cleaning frequency to once every hour, focusing on high-touch points like seats, shopping bags and kids’ showrooms. Premises will be disinfected during closing hours. 
#IKEA #IKEASingapore #Singapore #furniture #shopping #retail #CNAlifestyle (Pic: Aqil Haziq Mahmud)

IKEA will open on Friday (Jun 19) with strict safe distancing measures, although its food and beverage offerings and kids’ facilities will remain closed for now.

Its two outlets at Tampines and Alexandra will reduce opening hours, limit the number of people inside and close their car parks if queues get too long.

More workers will be deployed for crowd control inside and outside the building, including safe distancing ambassadors who will usher customers along.

Staff will increase the cleaning frequency to once every hour, focusing on high-touch points like seats, shopping bags and kids’ showrooms. Premises will be disinfected during closing hours. 
#IKEA #IKEASingapore #Singapore #furniture #shopping #retail #CNAlifestyle (Pic: Aqil Haziq Mahmud)

Hugging is one of the things people miss doing during this pandemic. If you need it, take precautions, according to a New York Times article.

Wear a mask. Hug outdoors. Try to avoid touching the other person’s body or clothes with your face and your mask. Also, don’t talk or cough while you’re hugging. And do it quickly. Approach each other and briefly embrace. Back away quickly so you don’t breathe into each other’s faces. Wash your hands afterward.

DON’T: HUG FACE-TO-FACE
When the shorter person looks up, their exhaled breath travels up into the taller person’s breathing zone. If the taller person is looking down, there is opportunity for the huggers’ exhaled and inhaled breaths to mingle.

DO: HUG FACING OPPOSITE DIRECTIONS
For a safe, full-body hug, turn your faces in opposite directions, which prevents you from directly breathing each other’s exhaled particles. Wear a mask.

DO: LET CHILDREN HUG YOU AROUND THE KNEES OR WAIST
Hugging at knee or waist level lowers risk for direct exposure to droplets and aerosols because faces are far apart. There is potential for the child’s face and mask to contaminate the adult’s clothing. So you might consider changing clothes, and wash your hands after a visit that includes hugs. The adult also should look away so as not to breathe down on the child.

DO: KISS YOUR GRANDCHILD ON THE BACK OF THE HEAD
In this scenario, the grandparent is minimally exposed to the child’s exhaled breath. The child could be exposed to the taller person’s breath, so kiss through a mask.

DO: HOLD YOUR BREATH
Holding your breath stops you exhaling any virus into their breathing zone, if you are unknowingly infected – and stops you inhaling any virus from them, if they are unknowingly infected.

DO: CHOOSE HUGS WISELY
Close friends and family? Sure. Casual hugs? Maybe not.

Read more on CNA Lifestyle, link in bio. #hugging #hugs #wellness #friends #family #missingyou #relationships (Art: The New York Times)

You might not recognise her because she’s wearing a mask, but that’s Joanne Peh who’s in China right now.

The Singaporean actress is in Guangzhou, where she celebrated the Chinese New Year with her family – and she’s chosen to stay for now with her two-year-old son and four-year-old daughter to “finish up some personal matters” regarding her children.

In an Instagram post on Jan 28, she wrote that husband, actor Qi Yuwu, was flying back to Singapore while she stayed put. Qi also posted on his own account how he had “mixed feelings” leaving his family.

Peh’s lengthy post painted a sober image of the situation in Guangzhou, saying the Wuhan virus has “caused widespread fear as people stay indoors and avoid visiting; masks, antibacterial sprays are sold out; restaurants are peddling raw ingredients outside their premise because no one is patronizing.” But she did end with words of encouragement: “To all who are separated from your loved ones, it isn’t a great feeling but stay strong, be safe and keep the light shining in your heart.” Stay safe, Joanne and family!

Read more on CNA Lifestyle, link in bio. #JoannePeh #QiYuwu #Wuhanvirus #coronavirus #Guangzhou #China #Singapore #actress (Photo: Instagram/joannepeh)

The Singaporean actress is in Guangzhou, where she celebrated the Chinese New Year with her family – and she’s chosen to stay for now with her two-year-old son and four-year-old daughter to “finish up some personal matters” regarding her children.

In an Instagram post on Jan 28, she wrote that husband, actor Qi Yuwu, was flying back to Singapore while she stayed put. Qi also posted on his own account how he had “mixed feelings” leaving his family.

Peh’s lengthy post painted a sober image of the situation in Guangzhou, saying the Wuhan virus has “caused widespread fear as people stay indoors and avoid visiting; masks, antibacterial sprays are sold out; restaurants are peddling raw ingredients outside their premise because no one is patronizing.” But she did end with words of encouragement: “To all who are separated from your loved ones, it isn’t a great feeling but stay strong, be safe and keep the light shining in your heart.” Stay safe, Joanne and family!

Read more on CNA Lifestyle, link in bio. #JoannePeh #QiYuwu #Wuhanvirus #coronavirus #Guangzhou #China #Singapore #actress (Photo: Instagram/joannepeh)

Happy CNY from us and our January CNA Luxury digital cover star Sonia Chew! Should your relatives start asking you why you’re not married yet, here are 10 humble suggestions for how you could end the conversation. Warning: This may or may not affect your overall hong bao tally. Invitations to steamboat dinners may also be rescinded. 😂

1. “I’m waiting to see how things work out with Harry and Meghan.”
2. “It’s a little complicated since I joined the circus. You know, with all the travelling and the elephants.”
3. “Actually, I met a fabulous Nigerian prince over email….”
4. “Good news! My boss has been saying the divorce will be final any day now!”
5. “Don’t want. Not until BTOs come in Millennial Pink. 😑”
6. “Maybe after the baby is born. Maternity bridal gowns are so tacky. Ugh.”
7. “It’s because you’ve set such a high bar with your perfect marriage, Aunty. So, really, it’s your fault. ✌🏻”
8. “Huat, ah! My new boyfriend’s CPF payout starts this year!”
9. “I would, but I’m allergic to commitment. Ooh, is that bak kwa?”
10. “Oh… your son didn’t tell you? Well, this is awkward… 😶”
#cny #chinesenewyear #instahumour #cnykeepsmiling #CNAlifestyle #CNAluxury

description:
If you were planning to catch Jackie Chan’s latest film over the Chinese New Year holidays, you’ll have to wait longer.

The releases of four Chinese movies, including Vanguard, have been delayed in Singapore after they were pulled from theatres in China due to concerns about the Wuhan virus. The other affected movies were: Animated feature Jiang Zi Ya: Legend Of Deification, action flick The Rescue and the comedy Detective Chinatown 3.

description:
[Turn up the volume!] 987 DJ, social media influencer and budding lifestyle maven Sonia Chew is CNA Luxury’s first digital cover star of 2020. And in the spirit of Chinese New Year, we’ve reimagined this thoroughly modern millennial as a beguiling pin-up moll typical of 1920s Shanghai in our little fashion film, Poster Girl.

Those old posters also provided suitable parallels for our full interview on CNA Luxury. They broke with how Chinese women were traditionally represented – these were women who didn’t conform. And Sonia’s never been a girl who feels the need to conform to what you think is an appropriate way for how she should live her life.

That’s why she says people shouldn’t underestimate millennials like her. “We come with a different type of tenacity. What amazes me about some younger people nowadays is their fearlessness to leap into the unknown and not simply settle for something that's deemed more socially acceptable.” And that's groovy in any era. Read the full story on CNA Luxury! Link in bio. #style #styleinspo #vintagestyle #chinoiserie #cny #chinesenewyear #soniachew #singapore #CNAluxury

Chinese New Year is just around the corner and for some people, that means it’s time for spring cleaning – if they can get around to actually letting go of things.

According to IMH, one in 50 people in Singapore display hoarding behaviour. Mayo Clinic meanwhile, says hoarding starts around the ages of 11 to 15 and gets worse with age.

There are many reasons why people hoard – sentimental reasons, as a mental illness – and there’s also a distinction between being a collector and being a hoarder. Read our in-depth story on hoarding, including how to get rid of things, on CNA Lifestyle, link in bio. #hoarding #hoarder #springcleaning #ChineseNewYear #CNY (Photo: Unsplash)

comments: this is like eating chicken rice without the chicken.
description:
Introducing: Singapore’s first pineapple-less pineapple tarts. Yes, a young company called BoTart has introduced pineapple tarts without the pineapple filling.

The folks behind BoTart did so because they loved everything about it – except for the jam. "Every year, we’d be forced to nibble the outer crust and wrap the jam in a tissue before tossing it – otherwise, the adults would give us a scolding, or we would get laughed at,” they shared.

BoTart currently offers two products: Pineappless Tarts (S$16.80), a jar of buttery no-pineapple-pineapple tarts; and Pineapple Glazed Tarts (S$18.80), which have homemade pineapple jam lightly brushed onto the top, so you can enjoy a hint of pineapple flavour without the sweet chewiness of actual pineapple filling. #pineappletart #ChineseNewYear #CNY #BoTart (Photo: BoTart)

BoTart currently offers two products: Pineappless Tarts (S$16.80), a jar of buttery no-pineapple-pineapple tarts; and Pineapple Glazed Tarts (S$18.80), which have homemade pineapple jam lightly brushed onto the top, so you can enjoy a hint of pineapple flavour without the sweet chewiness of actual pineapple filling. #pineappletart #ChineseNewYear #CNY #BoTart (Photo: BoTart)
